07742nam a22009015i 9780231557689DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315576897 a10.7312/asme208902doi  a(DE-B1597)638400  a(OCoLC)1342985455  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAN0080002bisacsh04a818.00822304aThe Best American Magazine Writing 2022 /ced. by Sid Holt. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tAcknowledgments -- tBodies on the Line -- tWe’re Already Barreling Toward the Next Pandemic -- tThese Precious Days -- tVenus Rising -- tThe Webb Space Telescope Will Rewrite Cosmic History. If It Works -- tThe Methane Hunters -- tWe Need to Change How We Talk About Abortion -- tThe Games We Play -- tThe Original Cowboys -- tInfinite Self -- tIs Jake Paul Bad for Boxing? Next Question -- tThe Wrong Daddy -- tPast Imperfect -- tBeyond Britney Abuse, Exploitation, and Death Inside America’s Guardianship Industry -- tPut on the Diamonds -- tWhat Do We Do About John James Audubon? -- tThe Collapse -- tTwenty Years Gone -- tCome with Me -- tPermissions -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Best American Magazine Writing 2022 presents a range of outstanding writing on timely topics, from in-depth reporting to incisive criticism: Kristin Canning calls for a change in how we talk about abortion (Women’s Health), and Ed Yong warns us about the next pandemic (The Atlantic). Matthieu Aikins provides a gripping eyewitness account of the Taliban’s seizure of Kabul (New York Times Magazine). Heidi Blake and Katie J. M. Baker’s “Beyond Britney” examines how people placed under legal guardianship are deprived of their autonomy (BuzzFeed News). Rachel Aviv profiles a psychologist who studies the fallibility of memory—and has testified for defendants including Harvey Weinstein and Bill Cosby (The New Yorker).The anthology includes dispatches from the frontiers of science, exploring why Venus turned out so hellishly unlike Earth (Popular Science) and detailing the potential of NASA’s James Webb Space Telescope (Quanta). It features celebrated writers, including Harper’s magazine pieces by Ann Patchett, whose “These Precious Days” is a powerful story of friendship during the pandemic, and Vivian Gornick, who offers “notes on humiliation.” Carina del Valle Schorske depicts the power of public dance after pandemic isolation (New York Times Magazine). And the NBA icon Kareem Abdul-Jabbar lauds the Black athletes who fought for social justice (AARP the Magazine). Amid the continuing reckoning with racism, authors reconsider tarnished figures. The Black ornithologist and birder J. Drew Lanham assesses the legacy of John James Audubon in the magazine that bears his name, and Jeremy Atherton Lin questions his youthful enthusiasm for Morrissey (Yale Review). Jennifer Senior writes about memory and the lingering grief felt for a friend killed on 9/11 (The Atlantic). The collection concludes with Nishanth Injam’s story of queer first love across religious boundaries, “Come with Me” (Georgia Review).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican prose literaturey21st centuryvPeriodicals. 0aAmerican prose literaturey21st century. 0aJournalismxAwardszUnited StatesvPeriodicals. 0aJournalismxAwardszUnited States. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Journalism.2bisacsh1 aAbdul-Jabbar, Kareem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAikins, Matthieu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAkintoye, Dotun, econtribut